Analysis of the Target Structure  
• Block Count & Layers  
From the photograph, the model is made of four total blocks arranged in two layers. The bottom (first) layer has two red arch‐shaped blocks set at right angles to each other, and the top (second) layer consists of two orange wedge blocks forming the “roof.”  

• Spatial Relationships  
1) On the ground layer, one red arch faces “front to back” while the other arch sits behind it turned 90 degrees (so its arch runs “side to side”). Pushed snugly together, their top surfaces create a flat platform.  
2) On the second (upper) layer, two orange triangular wedges rest side by side on that flat platform, pitched toward each other so that their hypotenuses meet in the middle, forming a ridged roof.  

Selecting the Required Blocks  
From the Dictionary image, the matching shapes and orientations are:  
• Red arch that opens “front to back”: Index 1  
• Red arch that opens “side to side”: Index 2  
• Left‐sloping orange roof wedge: Index 11  
• Right‐sloping orange roof wedge (mirror): Index 12  

Assembly Order  
Below is a simple step‐by‐step assembly sequence using those exact dictionary blocks (no extra rotation needed):
{
  Step1: Move block with index 1   // Place the front‐to‐back arch
  Step2: Move block with index 2   // Place the side‐to‐side arch behind it
  Step3: Move block with index 11  // Place the left‐sloping orange wedge on top
  Step4: Move block with index 12  // Place the right‐sloping orange wedge next to it
}
